<FONT SIZE="+1"><B>Waladen's Tactics in Permafrost</B></FONT><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
Hail!<BR><BR>
  
I am a level 6 warrior barbarian. It gets tedious walking around the peaks looking for experience, except for the skeletons carrying weapons than come in handy for trading and selling and polar bear cubs for tailoring ;-). A nice tactic for the plains on lower levels is to get a large group together on the edge of the plains. Send two or three "scouting" parties just across the ravines to draw an attack from polar bears, mammoth calfs, and snow leopards within sight of the rest of the party. Once they attack then run back to the rest of the group and then dispatch the creature. The advantage to this is that you don't have to worry so much about other creatures seeing you and attacking you also being closer to the passes. Getting killed is a bummer when you're trying to level up :-( . The other advantage is that if your group takes on more than it can handle, running back to the nearby guards helps get you out of a jam instead of getting killed.<BR><BR>
  
Also, I see alot of players buying torches and lanterns at lower levels. You don't need one until your ready to go to Black Burrow. Just click on options then display and turn the gamma all the way up. It kind of kills the graphic effects a bit but it makes you able to fight in the dark with a 2H slashing weapon and doesn't cost you precious cash. Even traveling between Halas and Everfrost is a lot easier after dark. A lot of beginners don't know about this "trick".<BR><BR>
  
As you get higher in levels, get an extra backpack and put extra armour and weapons in it as you get them. Stash it in a bank. If you get killed in a hard area to get to "AKA deep in the plains or in BB" , then you don't have to run back "naked and unarmed" to get your stuff. The disadvantage to this is if your full of items you might have to leave some on your corpse when you get back to it. But it sure beats getting into a nasty fight on the way out of food and drink and just able to hit, kick, and bash! I haven't tried this yet on EverQuest but but "stashing" has worked well in the past on other online RPG games and saves a lot of time and headaches in the past. You ought to try it with a new character to see if going from area to area erases the corpse.<BR><BR>
  
Never sell good items and weapons to a vendor. You can always get more out of it from another player and might help you form partnerships. I try to sell stuff for 1.5 - 2 times what I can sell it for to a vendor and even offer a money back trade if the items don't suit the players if they are not sure they want it. With some items for shamans and bards it might take a while for the right player to come along but they will eventually.<BR><BR>
  
This hasn't work for me yet but I have heard that saving useless items such as Woody Fungus and giving it to the guards near the guilds will sometimes get you a precious item or two from them. I also do this and try begging after it but it hasn't worked for me yet. It has for my stepson in Qeynos.<BR><BR>
  
